observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management:
Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment, within the prescribed period in accordance with the Section 124 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for LGUs, for the timely review and verification of the PPE accounts;
Thru the Inventory Committee, prepare the inventory report in accordance with the prescribed format in order to provide valuable information necessary in the reconciliation of balances;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the GSO to maintain Property Cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the Management require the following:
The Municipal Accountant to record in the books of accounts the costs of donated ambulances totaling P5,968,775.00 and the additional costs of purchased ambulances amounting to P3,070,740.00. Thereafter, compute the corresponding accumulated depreciation since its receipt until the year-end;
The GSO-Designate to ascertain the current location and condition of the ambulance costing P2,426,200.00 and to determine whether the benefit of its use exceeds the cost that could have been incurred in its repair.  However, if the vehicle is beyond repair due to the long years of neglect, we recommended that the same be subjected to disposal;
Ensure that all motor vehicles owned and operated by the Local Government Unit are insured to safeguard the government's interests in the event of unforeseen accidents;
Incorporate the donated vehicles in the inventory report to guarantee an accurate record of all motor vehicles;
Require the GSO-Designate to increase efforts in the management, receipt and issue of all properties of the Municipality and maintain records required by the aforementioned provisions; and
Ensure proper coordination between the Offices of the LGU and the GSO when it comes to the receipt of donated properties to ensure appropriate accounting and property management thereof.

We have recommended that the Management: 

A. Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality and submit Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment within the prescribed period for the timely review and verification of the PPE accounts; 

B. Thru the Inventory Committee, prepare the inventory report in accordance with the prescribed format in order to provide valuable information necessary in the reconciliation of balances; 

C. Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs; 

D. Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and E. Direct the GSO to maintain Property Cards (PCs) for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114 Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

