We recommended that:
The collecting officers remit their collections daily to the liquidating officer in compliance with Section 89(A) of the LTOM, 2nd Edition;
The liquidating officer strictly monitor the daily remittance of the collecting officers;
The Accountable Forms Custodian strictly update the CRAAF with the individual RAAF of the collecting officers to monitor and readily detect any unremitted collections from accountable forms; and
The Accountable Forms Custodian should not issue additional accountable forms to collecting officers with unremitted collections to avoid accumulation of cash in their custody.

We recommended that the Management:
Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment within the prescribed period for the timely review and verification of the PPE accounts;
Thru the Inventory Committee, prepare the inventory report in accordance with the prescribed format in order to provide valuable information necessary in the reconciliation of balances;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the GSO to maintain Property Cards (PCs) for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

a.	The Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to prepare and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list of taxpayers showing the names and the amounts due and collectible based on updated Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card to provide an accurate and reliable basis in setting up the Receivables from RPT and SET;

b.	The Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher to record the RPT/SET Receivables established at the beginning of the year based on the submitted duly certified list of taxpayers with the amount due and collectible for the year and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers to monitor tax collections and delinquencies;

c.	The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the RPT Receivable and SET Receivable set up at the beginning of the year and draw the appropriate adjusting entries, if necessary;

d.	The Municipal Treasury to implement a more intensive strategy in the collection of Real Property Tax in the Municipality; and 

e.	The concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 246 of RA No. 7160 and New Government Accounting System Manual for LGUs, Volume I.

